renames:  German Reinhard, Erwin.","German: possibly a habitational name from Riessen in Brandenburg.","German: variant of   Riesen  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Riesen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Kurt.","German and Swiss German:","habitational name from any of several places so named in Bavaria, Württemberg, and Tyrol."]}]},{"name":"Othon","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Some translate Otho 'happy' and Otto 'rich;' but they would seem to be the same name, for Otho of Freysingen, son of Leopold, Margrave of Austria, and of Agnes, daughter of the Emperor Henry IV., is also called Otto. It was the surname of a Roman emperor, and of one of the Roscian family; It comes from Old German od, excelling, happy, fortunate."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Othon II DE WITTELSBACH-DE DIESSEN was born in 1062, his father, Otton de Wittelsbach Scheyern de wittelsbach scheyern robertien, was 44 and his mother, Haziga (Hadegunde) Dießen, von Stifterin des Klosters Bayrischzell, was 36. He had at least 1 son with Richarde DE WEIMAR DE RATZHOFEN-DE REIPERSBERG. He died in 1127, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1062–1127":"1062–1127","1065–1139":"1065–1139","1083–1156":"1083–1156","1018–1072":"1018–1072","1027–1104":"1027–1104","4 DEC 1072":"4. detsember 1072","1065":"1065","1062":"1062","1072":"1072","1083":"1083","1018":"1018","1139":"1139","1127":"1127","7 January 1083":"7. jaanuar 1083","1104":"1104","1027":"1027","17 OCT 1104":"17. oktoober 1104","ABT 1057":"umbes 1057","1156":"1156","Bavaria, Germany":"Bayern, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1062–1127":"1062–1127","1065–1139":"1065–1139","1083–1156":"1083–1156","1018–1072":"1018–1072","1027–1104":"1027–1104","4 DEC 1072":"4. joulukuuta 1072","1065":"1065","1062":"1062","1072":"1072","1083":"1083","1018":"1018","1139":"1139","1127":"1127","7 January 1083":"7. tammikuuta 1083","1104":"1104","1027":"1027","17 OCT 1104":"17. lokakuuta 1104","ABT 1057":"noin 1057","1156":"1156","Bavaria, Germany":"Bayern, Saksa"},"fr":{"1062–1127":"1062–1127","1065–1139":"1065–1139","1083–1156":"1083–1156","1018–1072":"1018–1072","1027–1104":"1027–1104","4 DEC 1072":"4 décembre 1072","1065":"1065","1062":"1062","1072":"1072","1083":"1083","1018":"1018","1139":"1139","1127":"1127","7 January 1083":"7 janvier 1083","1104":"1104","1027":"1027","17 OCT 1104":"17 octobre 1104","ABT 1057":"environ 1057","1156":"1156","Bavaria, Germany":"Bayern, Allemagne","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Othon II DE WITTELSBACH-DE DIESSEN est né en 1062, son père, Otton de Wittelsbach Scheyern de wittelsbach scheye